or -- t10. Socio-Cultural Obligations and the Academic Career: The Dual Expectations Facing Black Canadian Academics -- tPart Three: Blackness: A Complicated Canadian Conversation -- tCommentary on Part Three: “Killing Us Softly” – with Questions -- t11. Fitting [Out-Fitting] In -- t12. The Caged Bird Still Sings in Harmony: The Academy, Spoken Word Poetry, and the Making of Community -- t13. States of Being:1 The Poet & Scholar as a Black, African, & Diasporic Woman -- t14. Intersectionality in Blackface: When Post-racial Nationalism Meets Black Feminism -- t15. Re-spatializing the Boundaries of Belonging: The Subversive Blackness of Muslim Women -- tPart Four: Black Pasts, Black Futurity -- tCommentary on Part Four: Surviving Anti-Blackness: Vulnerability, Speaking Back, and Building Black Futurity -- t16. (Re)situating Black Studies at York University: Unsilencing the Past, Locating the Present, Routing Futures -- t17. Community Service Learning and Anti-Blackness: The Cost of Playing with Fire on the Black Female Body -- t18. Blackness and the Limits of Institutional Goodwill -- t19. Leadership in Neoliberal Times: A Road to Nowhere -- t20. Vocation of the Black Scholar in the Neoliberal Academy: A Love Story -- t21. The Changing Same: Black Lives Matter, the Work of History, and the Historian’s Craft -- t22. Charting Black Presence and Futures in the Canadian Academy -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe essays in Nuances of Blackness in the Canadian Academy make visible the submerged stories of Black life in academia. They offer fresh historical, social, and cultural insights into what it means to teach, learn, research, and work while Black. In daring to shift from margin to centre, the book’s contributors confront two overlapping themes. First, they resist a singular construction of Blackness that masks the nuances and multiplicity of what it means to be and experience the academy as a Black body. Second, they challenge the stubborn durability of anti-Black tropes, the dehumanization of Blackness, persistent deficit ideology, and the tyranny of low expectations that permeate the dominant idea of Blackness in the White colonial imagination. Operating at the intersections of discourse and experience, contributors reflect on how Blackness shapes academic pathways, ignites complicated and often difficult conversations, and re-imagines Black pasts, presents, and futures. This unique collection contributes to the articulation of more nuanced understandings of the ways in which Blackness is made, unmade, and remade in the academy and the implications for interrelated dynamics across and within post-secondary education, Black communities in Canada, and global Black diasporas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBlack peoplexEducation (Higher)zCanada. 0aBlack peoplexRace identityzCanada. 0aCollege teachers, BlackzCanada. 0aDiscrimination in higher educationzCanada. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh  aBlack Canadian studies.  aBlackness.  aCanadian academy.  aanti-Black racism.  aautobiography.  aeducation.1 aAbdi, Ali A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmponsah, Evelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackett, Adelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrichlow, Wesley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaniel, Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouglas, Delia D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDryden, Omisoore H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFearon, Gervan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc